occurrenceRemarks: Abundant; Prostrate or trailing plant that grows in matlike clumps. Stems have retrorse bristles that ""stick"" to surfaces. Petals white.
habitat: In woods on fairly flat ground, growing over other herbaceous plants.
locality: Blue Ridge Center for Environmental Stewardship. Along southeastern side of Farmstead Loop trail about 30 m from Piney Run.

occurrenceRemarks: Abundant; Stems no more than 6 cm tall, usually ascending, sometimes erect. Corollas about 2 mm wide at most, blue, with four petals.
habitat: On recently mowed grass in full sun on west-facing hillside in field.
associatedTaxa: Veronica persica, Trifolium campestre, Medicago lupulina, Plantago lanceolata, Anthoxanthum odoratum
locality: Blue Ridge Center for Environmental Stewardship. On west side of gravel road along Sawmill Field located centrally between north and south parts of field, within 10 m of gravel.

occurrenceRemarks: Occasional; Same group as Elizabeth McMurchie collection #1074. Meter and a half tall shrub with hollow mature stems. Flowers showy, yellow.
habitat: At base of northwest-facing hillside, near abandoned ruins of log cabins, fairly shaded.
locality: Blue Ridge Center for Environmental Stewardship. Near the junction of Farmstead Loop and Piney Run Spur Trail, about 5 m southeast of Farmstead Loop Trail. Next to a historic log cabin.

occurrenceRemarks: Frequent; Stems green-purple. Flowers heads hemispheric, discoid, occasionally with 2 ray flowers, disk florets orange-yellow.
habitat: Growing rooted in water, several cm deep, with majority of plant above water, on gravel in pond.
associatedTaxa: Alisma subcordatum, Ludwigia alternifolia, Hypericum mutilum, Lycopus virginicus, Scirpus cyperinus, Lobelia cardinalis, Mimulus ringens, Ludwigia palustris
locality: Blue Ridge Center for Environmental Stewardship. Growing at southeast edge of Gordon Pond.

occurrenceRemarks: Occasional; Appears intermediate between ssp. latiusculum and ssp. pseudocaudatum. Leaf segment margins glabrous. Terminal tip of basal most pinnule of basal pinna short. Terminal segments of pinnules 2-4x as long as broad.
habitat: At southern edge of small, north facing hill at edge of woods in partial shade overlooking seep onto meadow
locality: Blue Ridge Center for Environmental Stewardship. About 40 m south of Butterfly Alley Trail about 70 m east of Sweet Run.

habitat: In patch of Microstegium vimineum just north of trail, in partial shade, on rocky soil.
locality: Blue Ridge Center for Environmental Stewardship. Just north of the intersection of Arnold Trail and Little Turtle Trail.

occurrenceRemarks: Abundant; Ray florets up to about 12, all florets goldenrod-yellow.
habitat: In field surrounded by grasses and other Solidago juncea under powerlines in full sun.
associatedTaxa: Monarda fistulosa, Rubus flagellaris, Rudbeckia hirta, Asclepias syriaca, Eutrochium fistulosum
locality: Blue Ridge Center for Environmental Stewardship. Under powerlines about 30 m east of Sweet Run.

occurrenceRemarks: Flowers deep blue-purple. Root not collected due to low numbers.
habitat: At base of south-facing slope, in shade, about 3 m east of unpaved path.
locality: Meadowlark Botanical Gardens Potomac Valley Collection. Southeast of southern-most bridge.

occurrenceRemarks: Occasional; Head inflorescence, in early fruit, with pappus dingy white. Margins of phyllaries are green.
habitat: Growing in tall grass near gravel road, in full sun.
associatedTaxa: Melilotus officinalis, Melilotus albus, Andropogon gerardii, Phleum pratense, Leucanthemum vulgare, Dianthus armeria, Rudbeckia hirta, Echinacea purpurea, Asclepias syriaca, Coreopsis lanceolata
locality: Blue Ridge Center for Environmental Stewardship. Under powerlines in tall grass about 35 m east of intersection of Butterfly Alley and Sawmill Field gravel road.

occurrenceRemarks: Common; Ray florets white, disk florets yellow to purplish.
habitat: In tall grass in Sawmill Field on slight east-facing hillside.
associatedTaxa: Symphyotrichum pilosum, Pseudognaphalium obtusifolium, Rubus flagellaris, Tridens flavus, Bromus sterilis, Elephantopus carolinianus
locality: Blue Ridge Center for Environmental Stewardship. Eastern part of Sawmill Field about 50 m east of gravel road, about 100 m north of horse trail parking lot.

habitat: Growing on muddy soil at edge of trees in partial shade, near small stream leading to pond.
locality: Blue Ridge Center for Environmental Stewardship. At southwestern edge of Gordon Pond.

habitat: Throughout Sawmill Field in full sun, both in mowed and unmowed parts of grass.
locality: Blue Ridge Center for Environmental Stewardship. Growing in Sawmill Field near to parking lot.

habitat: Growing in mowed grass in full sun.
locality: Blue Ridge Center for Environmental Stewardship. About 4 m north of entrance to Mountain View Farm, south of driveway of main entrance.

habitat: Growing on mossy rocks broken off of rock formation on east-facing dry hillside.
locality: Blue Ridge Center for Environmental Stewardship. A little over 100 m north of Farmstead Loop's northernmost, highest-elevation point.

occurrenceRemarks: Common; Stems slender, weak, with culms ascending to sprawling.
habitat: Growing at edge of trees under powerlines, near patch of Microstegium vimineum.
locality: Blue Ridge Center for Environmental Stewardship. At western intersection of Farmstead Loop and Derry Loop.

occurrenceRemarks: Frequent; Intermediate between var. perenne and var. aristatum. Has florets less than 11, like var. perenne, but awned lemmas, like var. aristatum.
habitat: One of tall grasses under powerlines in full sun.
associatedTaxa: Melilotus officinalis, Melilotus albus, Andropogon gerardii, Phleum pratense, Dianthus armeria, Achillea millefolium, Dactylis glomerata, Bromus sterilis
locality: Blue Ridge Center for Environmental Stewardship. At the intersection of the gravel road along Sawmill Field and Butterfly Alley.

habitat: In patch of moss on a boulder, partially shaded by trees.
locality: Blue Ridge Center for Environmental Stewardship. North of Arnold Trail by about 1 m, about 400 m east of Sweet Run

habitat: Near high elevation point of trail, in leaf litter beneath Ulmus rubra.
locality: Blue Ridge Center for Environmental Stewardship. Along eastern leg of Sweet Run Loop, on eastern side of trail, within 3 m of trail.

occurrenceRemarks: Colonial. Most stems sterile. Flowers white.
habitat: In shade within 2 m of asphalt trail at top of wooded hill.
locality: Meadowlark Botanical Gardens Potomac Valley Collection. At northwestern entrance to collection near sign for garden entrance.

habitat: On fairly steep but short hill, in partial shade from trees.
locality: Blue Ridge Center for Environmental Stewardship. At far western end of Derry Loop, about 1 m east of trail.

occurrenceRemarks: Frequent; Same group as Elizabeth McMurchie Collection #1180 and 1181. Perigynia immature.
habitat: On slightly damp soil near trail, growing near small, mossy rocks.
locality: Blue Ridge Center for Environmental Stewardship. On southern side of Farmstead Loop trail about 20 m from Piney Run, 100 m west of junction with Old Bridge Trail.

occurrenceRemarks: Occasional; Near to where Elizabeth McMurchie collection #757 and 758 were found. Same group as Elizabeth McMurchie collection #1322 and 1323. Stems up to about 1.5 m tall. Inflorescences vary by plant, axillary or terminal, racemes or panicles, with many flowers. Corollas yellow with large, brown stamens.
habitat: Significantly fewer in number this year. In full sun, standing above most surrounding tall grasses.
associatedTaxa: Tridens flavus, Asclepias tuberosa var. tuberosa, Asclepias syriaca, Solanum carolinense, Symphyotrichum pilosum
locality: Blue Ridge Center for Environmental Stewardship. About 15 m east of eastern mown path through western Sawmill Field.

habitat: Same group as Elizabeth McMurchie collection #112 and 113. Within 1 m of trail, on recently mowed grass, in partial shade.
locality: Blue Ridge Center for Environmental Stewardship. At north side of Sweet Run Loop trail, near where the stream crosses Butterfly Alley Trail.
